    "explanation": "Correct Answer: C\n\nDetailed Explanation & Step-by-step Solution:\nWhen a train crosses a pole, it covers a distance equal to its own length.\nLength of train = 150 metres\nTime taken to cross the pole = 15 seconds\nSpeed of the train = Length of train / Time = 150 / 15 = 10 m/s\n\nWhen the train crosses a bridge, the total distance covered is the sum of the length of the train and the length of the bridge.\nLength of bridge = 250 metres\nTotal distance = 150 + 250 = 400 metres\n\nTime taken to cross the bridge = Total distance / Speed of the train\nTime taken = 400 / 10 = 40 seconds.\n\nShortcut Method:\nTo cross 150 m, it takes 15 seconds (Ratio = 10 m/s).\nTo cross train + bridge = 150 + 250 = 400 m, it will take 400 / 10 = 40 seconds.\n\nCommon Mistakes:\nUsing only the length of the bridge (250 m) as the distance when crossing the bridge, resulting in 25 seconds.\n\nExtra Learning Point:\nAlways remember to add the train's own length to the length of any platform, bridge, or another train it is crossing.\n\nPYQ Connection:\nTime, Speed and Distance train problems are heavily asked in HSSC CET Group D exams.",
