    "text": "A shopkeeper offers two successive discounts of 20% and 10% on an item. What is the single equivalent discount percent? / एक दुकानदार एक वस्तु पर 20% और 10% की दो क्रमिक छूट प्रदान करता है। एकल समतुल्य छूट प्रतिशत क्या है?",
    "options": [
      "25% / 25%",
      "28% / 28%",
      "30% / 30%",
      "32% / 32%"
    ],
    "correctIndex": 1,
    "explanation": "Correct Answer: B\n\nDetailed Explanation & Step-by-step Solution:\nLet the marked price (MP) of the item be ₹100.\nFirst discount = 20% of ₹100 = ₹20\nPrice after first discount = 100 - 20 = ₹80\n\nSecond discount = 10% of ₹80 = ₹8\nPrice after second discount (Selling Price) = 80 - 8 = ₹72\n\nTotal discount offered = Marked Price - Selling Price = 100 - 72 = ₹28\nSingle equivalent discount percentage = (Total discount / MP) × 100% = (28 / 100) × 100% = 28%.\n\nShortcut Method:\nSingle equivalent discount of two successive discounts d1% and d2% is given by:\nEquivalent Discount = d1 + d2 - (d1 × d2) / 100\nEquivalent Discount = 20 + 10 - (20 × 10) / 100 = 30 - 2 = 28%.\n\nCommon Mistakes:\nSimply adding the two discount percentages: 20% + 10% = 30%.\n\nExtra Learning Point:\nSuccessive discounts are multiplicative, not additive. The order of discounts does not change the final equivalent discount.\n\nPYQ Connection:\nSuccessive discount is a highly recurring question in HSSC CET, SSC CGL, and CHSL prelims.",
