    "text": "Read the passage carefully and answer the question that follows:\n\nPlastics have become an indispensable part of modern life, but their environmental impact is devastating. Because plastics are highly durable and resistant to degradation, they persist in ecosystems for hundreds of years. Most plastic waste ends up in landfills or oceans, where it breaks down into microplastics, entering the food chain and posing severe health hazards to marine life and humans alike. Addressing this crisis requires a global shift toward circular economies and biodegradable alternatives.\n\nBased on the passage, why do plastics persist in ecosystems for hundreds of years?",
    "options": [
      "Because they break down into microplastics very quickly.",
      "Because they are highly durable and resistant to degradation.",
      "Because they are mostly disposed of in landfills and oceans.",
      "Because they have become an indispensable part of modern life."
    ],
    "correctIndex": 1,
    "explanation": "Correct Answer: Option B (Because they are highly durable and resistant to degradation.)\n\nDetailed Explanation:\n- According to the second sentence of the passage: 'Because plastics are highly durable and resistant to degradation, they persist in ecosystems for hundreds of years.'\n- This directly explains the longevity of plastic waste in the environment.\n- Option A is incorrect because microplastic breakdown is a consequence, not the reason for their persistence.\n- Option C describes where they end up, not why they don't decompose.\n- Option D describes their role in human life, not their physical/chemical persistence.\n\nStep-by-step Solution:\n1. Scan the passage for the keyword 'persist' or 'hundreds of years'.\n2. Locate the sentence: 'Because plastics are highly durable and resistant to degradation, they persist in ecosystems for hundreds of years.'\n3. Match the reason ('highly durable and resistant to degradation') with the options.\n4. Option B matches the text exactly.\n\nShortcut Method:\nIn Reading Comprehension, avoid selecting options that are factually true in real life but not mentioned as the cause/effect in the passage. Use direct keyword matching (e.g., matching 'persist in ecosystems' to the 'because' clause) to find the answer swiftly.\n\nCommon Mistakes:\nStudents sometimes choose options like C because it represents a common fact about plastic pollution, but it does not answer the specific 'why' question asked in the text. Always stick strictly to the text of the passage.\n\nExtra Learning Point:\nReading Comprehension strategy:\n- First, read the question and identify key terms.\n- Scan the passage for those terms.\n- Read one sentence before and after to get the complete context before choosing the answer.\n\nPYQ Connection:\nPassage-based reading comprehension questions in HSSC CET Group D exams are direct and factual. Testing comprehension through environmental or science-based topics is a very common pattern in recent CET shifts.",
