    "id": "q-hssc-cet-m4-38",
    "text": "Statement: \"All scientists are researchers. Raman is a scientist.\" / कथन: \"सभी वैज्ञानिक शोधकर्ता हैं। रमन एक वैज्ञानिक है।\"",
    "options": [
      "Valid deductive reasoning / वैध निगमनात्मक तर्क",
      "Invalid reasoning / अवैध तर्क",
      "Inductive reasoning only / केवल आगमनात्मक तर्क",
      "A logical fallacy / एक तार्किक भ्रांति"
    ],
    "correctIndex": 0,
    "explanation": "This is a textbook example of valid deductive reasoning (a categorical syllogism): given a universal premise (\"All scientists are researchers\") and a specific premise (\"Raman is a scientist\"), the conclusion (\"Raman is a researcher\") necessarily and logically follows. / यह वैध निगमनात्मक तर्क (श्रेणीबद्ध न्यायवाक्य) का एक उत्कृष्ट उदाहरण है: एक सार्वभौमिक आधार वाक्य (\"सभी वैज्ञानिक शोधकर्ता हैं\") और एक विशिष्ट आधार वाक्य (\"रमन एक वैज्ञानिक है\") को देखते हुए, निष्कर्ष (\"रमन एक शोधकर्ता है\") अनिवार्य रूप से और तार्किक रूप से अनुसरण करता है।\n\n**Shortcut Method:** If a conclusion must be true whenever the premises are true, the reasoning is deductive and valid — this is the simplest test to apply.\n**Exam Tip:** Deductive reasoning moves from general rules to specific conclusions; inductive reasoning moves from specific observations to general rules — know this distinction for exam definitions.\n**Extra Learning Point:** This specific structure (All A are B; X is A; therefore X is B) is known as a categorical syllogism in classical logic and is the most basic, reliably valid reasoning form.",
    "sectionName": "Reasoning Ability",
    "testId": "test-hssc-cet-full-4"
