    "correctIndex": 1,
    "explanation": "Since the quoted speech is a direct question, the question mark must be placed inside the closing quotation marks, immediately after \"it.\" The sentence then continues with the unquoted reporting clause \"she asked,\" ending with a period (not shown as the sentence is part of a larger context, but the structure here is correct as written). Option A incorrectly uses a comma instead of a question mark for direct speech that is a question; Options C and D place the punctuation marks incorrectly outside the quotes or in the wrong position. / चूंकि उद्धृत वाक्य एक प्रत्यक्ष प्रश्न है, प्रश्न चिह्न को समापन उद्धरण चिह्नों के अंदर, \"it\" के ठीक बाद रखा जाना चाहिए। विकल्प A गलती से अल्पविराम का उपयोग करता है; विकल्प C और D विरामचिह्नों को गलत स्थान पर रखते हैं।\n\n**Exam Tip:** For direct questions inside quotation marks, the question mark always goes inside the closing quotes, and it replaces the comma that would otherwise separate the quote from the reporting clause.\n**Extra Learning Point:** This rule contrasts with cases where the entire sentence (not just the quoted part) is a question — for example: Did she say, \"It is late\"? — there, the question mark goes outside the quotes since the question applies to the whole sentence.",
